title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 3913 9mm 8+1 Round Compact in Case + Extras - RARE Excellent Condition!
postcontent: The Smith & Wesson 3913 9mm pistol was sold to the public from 1990 to 1999 and became what is commonly accepted as "the finest compact pistol Smith & Wesson ever made". This pistol was manufactured 1/11/1991 and has the machined flash chrome trigger and hammer that were later replaced with molded black parts to save cost.    The aluminum alloy frame and stainless steel slide combine for a weight of just 23.8 ozs. unloaded and perfect for concealealed carry. The full 3 finger grip houses 8 round magazines. 2 with a curved buttplate suitable for even large hands are included along with an extra flat interchangeable buttplate some prefer for concealed carry.    Even though this pistol only has a 3.5" barrel, it's accuracy is as good or better than my 4" full size models. It comes with Lo-Mount Novak 3 white dot sights. The action is called Traditional Double Action (TDA) which describes a longer 1st shot trigger pull which cocks the hammer, and single action short crisp trigger pull on subsequent shots.  An ambidextrous safety/decocker is featured for convenience and ultimate safety especially when keeping a round chambered.This is a handsome pistol you'd be proud to own which has been well cared for as you can see. The finish is simply excellent as are the internals and the recoil spring is brand new. A receipt for it from S&W and the original owner's manual are included in a nice case like it came in, not the original.I'm including a like new DeSantis 065-82 black leather Paddle holster and a Bianchi Model 6D ATB™ inside waistband holster along with 50 rounds of range ammo to get you started.    You simply can't wear out a 3rd Generation S&W pistol and they just keep going up in price. I like to think of my other 3 as a fun investment!No trades please. More pictures gladly provided upon request. Priority Mail shipping to your FFL available if a local transaction is not possible.

title: For Sale:  USFA Rodeo
postcontent: This is a USFA (United States Firearms Manufacturing) Rodeo model SAA Colt .38 special revolver, with a 5 ½” barrel. This gun looks as if it has seen slight use. It is rendered in USFA’s Rodeo Matte Blue finish and presentation and checkered US black synthetic composite grips. This model is not just for looks or occasional use but was also designed to be used by Cowboy Action Shooting (SASS) enthusiasts in shooting competitions. Its Matte Blue finish reduces sun glare that a polished finish throws off and the checkered grips help the shooter maintain a solid non-slip grip while handling the gun. This gun is like new in box and was made by USFA, which is now out of business. In the opinion of many collectors, writer/reviewers, and enthusiasts, these  reproduction single action revolvers made by USFA are the acknowledged “best in class” of the Colt style reproduction manufacturers, including Colt itself, as well as Uberti and other high end repro manufacturers. USFA SAA revolvers are celebrated for their unparalleled adherence to original model 1873 and later model specs, exceeding even first generation Colt originals for quality and detail. In addition, this revolver has been "slicked up" by Long Hunter Shooting Supply making an already excellent pistol even better. Also has the low profile hammer for faster target acquisition. One of two available with consecutive serial numbers.

title: For Sale:  Walther G22 Bullpup .22 LR rifle
location: Cary, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: For sale is a Walther G22 rifle in excellent condition, with the laser attachment, UTG bipod, original hard case, and two original 10-round magazines. I am the original and sole owner.The rifle is missing its original charging handle, and I have replaced it with one that I mocked up, as you can see in the photos. The replacement functions exactly like the original -- there's no play in it and it's comfortable to use. I also have additional long machine screws to fit the bolt so you can make your own version with plastic or metal standoffs if you want.Condition:The bore is in immaculate condition, but I was unable to get a good photo of it. There is a small patch of minor pitting on the top of the barrel where the metal is first exposed. It's very difficult to see in person. There's some finish wear on the barrel where it meets the red sliding safety indicators, and some wear on the ends of the disassembly pins. Other than that, there's not really any wear or cosmetic problems to speak of.The case (not pictured) is in good, functional condition. It shows plenty of use, including some damage to the foam inside, but is fully functional. I actually have been using it for lots of other smaller guns when I am not taking the G22 to the range.History:The gun has around 3000 rounds through it. Bulk ammo works well. I have had good luck with many different types of .22 LR. Early on, it didn't like Remington Golden Bullet, but either it "broke in" or Remington changed their ammo, because it seems to run fine with it now. Several months after buying the gun, I sent it off for repair because the trigger bar (connecting the trigger back to the sear) was able to bend too much, causing a "squishy" trigger. Smith and Wesson replaced the part and sent it back much better. I haven't had a problem with it since.Overall, the gun handles and operates very well and is amazingly accurate for a semi-auto. The main negative is that it's a pain to take apart to clean (similar to a Ruger Mark 2 or 3 in annoyance level). The good news is that a bore snake and an external wipe-down is really all that's necessary 90% of the time. The gun tolerates lots of internal dirt and fouling.I'd recommend the gun for any bullpup enthusiasts or for rimfire action competitions, due to its handling characteristics and super-short overall length.Asking $325 for everything. Other offers considered, but I'm in no hurry to sell the rifle, so don't waste your time with a low-ball offer. No trades.Pick up in Cary is GREATLY preferred. If you need it shipped, you'll need to add the cost of shipping and the outgoing FFL fee, which I would estimate at $55 total. I'll also need a picture or scan of your driver's license, regardless of delivery method.Thanks for looking!
